				<td rowspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" style="text-align: justify;" width="100%" valign=top>
				<DIV>
<P><STRONG>EverQuest Fan Fiction</STRONG></P>
<P><IMG src="http://newsletters.station.sony.com/eq1/images/en/content/fan_fiction.gif" align=left vspace=2 border=0 NOSEND="1">We have an incredibly talented and creative fan base and we are pleased to bring you the first in a series of three installments of Fan Fiction by Hassan al’Nasir (Karana).</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><STRONG>Last Voyage – Part 1</STRONG></P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>Lying upon the half rotten mattress, Caleb was certain of only one thing and that was that he was dying. Throughout his life he thought that when the time came, he would fear it, fight it off, or find some way to deny that it was taking place. His life had never been one of certainty or stability? What sailor’s ever was? From the spires of Erudin to the piers of Freeport, there was not a stretch of ocean or isolated islet in which a man or woman could not find themselves a grave.<BR><BR>Once, in a particularly fierce storm, he had been thrown from the forecastle to the deck, and for the rest of his days carried a limp to remind him of the incident. It also reminded him of how worse it could have been, for his companion had been thrown overboard in that very same storm. They made all the appropriate prayers, all the traditional offerings, but the sea does not give up its dead so easily. He was never found.<BR><BR>Closing his eyes, he thought about what it would be like. The pain until now had been excruciating, and he believed it would as the Artificers had explained in their doctrine, that the body as a machine would begin to fail, and only when it was finally beyond repair would it be released from all its functions. He was fairly certain that whatever waited for him, it could be no crueler than the fever which was sapping not only his strength, but his will as well.<BR><BR>Opening his eyes a sliver, even the flickering candle which illuminated his cabin seemed as bright as the sun itself, Caleb tried to gasp. It came out as a hacking cough. They were leagues away from the shore; there was no way that this could be possible.<BR><BR>"Merinda?"<BR><BR>"I am here, and there is nothing left to fear?"</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P align=center>* * *</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>"I tell you sir, straight out and now, that if this much longer keeps up, there be not a one who'll be left the sail for the next shipment."<BR><BR>Patrician nodded to the little man who spoke with the sailor's lilt. He brushed the sleeves of his velvet frock coat, pulled at the white lace cuffs, and examined the tar stained piece of canvas which covered the perfect outline of a human body. He shook his head, smiling slightly at the thought of the sailor next to him. Service to the Militia often </P>
<P>marked a man in many subtle ways, but Patrician was not one of them. <BR><BR>The skin of his rich, dark brown forehead betrayed no hint of his advancing years, not a wrinkle of worry or doubt, and his green eyes sparked with intensity. He had no doubt that the sailor had been expecting some bored functionary or hard nosed member of the Militia. <BR><BR>"Really, do you think I would be here if Lucan did not think this was of some importance?"&nbsp; </P>
<P>The little man shook his head, stringy brown hair whipping about as he did so.<BR><BR>"No, no, no sir, that said I did not at all, it's just that it's long been a time since Lucan has been interested a bit in what goes on down here?" <BR><BR>Patrician sniffed, lifting the corner of the canvas with the tip of his hard soled riding boot.<BR><BR>"A fever? Preceded by dizziness and general lassitude?" <BR><BR>"Sir?" <BR><BR>Patrician brought a hand to his face, "Was he tired and off balance?" <BR><BR>"Yes sir, days we were into the trip, and he squawked, pardon sir, he complained loud long and all about how his eyes were on fire. We found on the floor him we did, the sixth or seventh day out. Died in his cabin just the day before today he did, and the courier we had aboard with us, he sent word to the Militia he did."<BR><BR>Patrician nodded, and turned from the canvas covered body. His eyes rested upon The Harlequin, a three masted merchant ship registered to the city of Freeport which sat at the end of the pier. A bored looking longshoreman was heaving barrels over the side into the bay. Whatever sickness had overtaken the sailor, the authorities could not risk its spread into the city. The cargo of fine wine from Qeynos, worth thousands, was now destined for the silty bottom of the harbor. The sailors were confined to their ship, apart from the weasel of a captain. The Priests of Marr had confirmed that whatever had befallen the ship, it had not spread to the man who commanded it.<BR><BR>"Well, commit this particular soul to the deep, and I will get back to you within a few days."<BR><BR>"Sir?"<BR><BR>"I do not have time to stand here arguing with you, just do it. Someone will be down to speak with you later."<BR><BR>Patrician stalked off towards the harbor masters office, wondering exactly why he had been assigned to deal with this particular problem.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P align=center>* * *</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>"Because I asked you to, old man"<BR><BR>Smirking, Patrician sniffed at the glass of wine in his hand. Across from him, Ingival was paring his fingernails with a stiletto, his pinched features, long tapering nose and wispy goatee reminding him as always of a rat.<BR><BR>"I dare say I should be the one giving you the orders? Captain."<BR><BR>Ingival snorted, "No need for sarcasm, finger waggler. Lucan knows his business, and that business has me in charge of the Guard. You, you're a book banging fop he retains for reasons only the devils themselves can fathom. If I tell you to walk back end first to the land of the hairy feet, you'll do it and like it. You're a corpse caster, a Necromancer, and all I need to know is that you were asked into this situation because you prefer the cold, loose lips of the dead to living flesh."<BR><BR>Patrician looked over the rim of his glass at Ingival, eyebrow raised quizzically.<BR><BR>"You're fairly certain of yourself Captain.&nbsp; Tell me, if I am so desperately loathed, why even stomach my presence?"<BR><BR>The Captain of the Guard snorted and then spat into the straw which covered the floor next to the table.<BR><BR>"Because I was ordered to."<BR><BR>"Charming?"</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>"Isn't it?"<BR><BR>An uncomfortable silence followed the air between the two men thick with tension and barely restrained anger. The sound of footsteps, hard boots against damp cobblestone, punctured the silence, and Ingival rose from his seat.<BR><BR>"My dealings with you are finished, necromancer. One of my men has been assigned to assist you with this particular case. I haven't time in the day to go chasing after dead sailors whose lives matter not a whit to even their own mothers. I'll expect your report in a week."<BR><BR>Ingival opened the door, surprising the lithe young man whose arm was raised, ready to grasp the handle. His close cropped hair, shaved nearly to the scalp and leaving only blonde stubble, was indication enough that he was one of the Militia. The polished black boots, and the grey breeches tucked into the top, completed the impression. Even though he wore a torn and tar stained tunic, evidently a feeble attempt to mix in with the sailors on the docks, the youth reeked of inexperience.&nbsp; Possibly a squire to one of the more important officers in the Militia.<BR><BR>"Aron, that finely dressed fop over there is Patrician. Whatever you have on these waterlogged carcasses, you share. EVERYTHING. Am I clear on that?"<BR><BR>Aron glanced over at Patrician nervously and then looked up at Ingival. <BR><BR>"Clear sir."<BR><BR>Patrician finished off the wine in his glass. Things were definitely going to prove interesting, and for all the wrong reasons.<BR><BR><BR><EM>To be continued…</EM></P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><STRONG>Author Bio:</STRONG></P>
<P>Jeff Franzmann (Hassan al'Nasir on Karana) has been playing EverQuest since it was in Beta, and while he's taken some time off to explore other worlds, he always returns to Norrath. A technical supervisor in Winnipeg, Manitoba, the long cold winters have provided him with ample opportunities to indulge in two of his favorite hobbies; writing and gaming, all while raising a family consisting of his fiance Tania, their son Aubrey, three cats, a dog, and assorted fish scattered across two aquariums.</P></DIV>
				
